result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Denzel T. Sanders in court with attorney James Ritland regarding 14CF99, 14CF118 & 14CF196 and Charles D Betthauser regarding 15CF54 & 15CF97.  Gerald R. Fox appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Victim notification complied with. No restitution due at this time. Defendant plead no contest to Ct. 1 in 14CF99; amended Ct. 1 in 15CF54; and Ct. 1 in 15CF97. Defendant plead guilty to Ct. 1 in 14CF118. Court advised defendant of the charge in each of the cases and potential penalties. Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, elements and constitution rights. Defendant understood. Defense stipulated to a factual basis for the plea. Court found the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights and entered his plea. Court found a factual basis exists. Court accepts defendant's plea of no contest to Ct. 1 in 14CF99; amended Ct. 1 in 15CF54; and Ct. 1 in 15CF97 and guilty plea to Ct. 1 in 14CF118. Court ordered Ct. 2 in 14CF99, Ct. 2 in 14CF118, Ct. 1 in 14CF196, Ct. 2 in 15CF54 and Cts. 2 and 3 in 15CF97 dismissed but read-in. Pre-sentence investigation shall be due in 60 days and available to the parties 10 days before sentencing. Bond conditions continue.
